1. Introduction¶

The continuous discovery of exoplanets provides humanity with the hope of not only expansion into deep space, but to potentially colonize other planets. While there are still travel challenges to overcome, we can at least begin to consider some destination options.

This research project will compare the differences in exoplanet mass for exoplanets whose host star has a stellar mass greater than or equal to our sun against those orbiting a host star with a mass less than our sun. Additionally, we will investigate differences in orbital periods and in distance from our solar system. The goal of this research, however, is two-fold. While it will examine the specific properties outlined above, the overarching goal is to benefit all of humanity by providing a framework for the analysis of exoplanets in determining their viability and desirability as a target for human colonization.

Although this research strives to contribute to the scientific community, it's primary purpose is to reinforce student comprehension of research design and statistical methods. Accordingly, the hypotheses and ensuing analyses contained herein are based on parameter ranges chosen to strike a compromise between sufficient sample sizes and exoplanet habitability. This will be explained in more detail below.

Expansion and colonization¶

  • Running out of space and time (on Earth)
  • over 4,000 exoplanets discovered, but only 55 are considered habitable
  • So, how can we target an exoplanet for colonization, and find another home for humanity?

2. Hypotheses¶

H_0 (Null): There is no significant difference between the average mass of exoplanets whose host star's mass is greater than or equal to the sun versus exoplanets whose host star's mass is less than the sun.

H_a (Alt): There is a significant difference between the average mass of exoplanets whose host star's mass is greater than or equal to the sun versus exoplanets whose host star's mass is less than the sun.

Similar hypotheses for orbital period and distance from our solar system will be tested as well.

Find an environment that resembles our own.¶

3. Data¶

Data Set Overview

NASA maintains an exoplanet data set with composite data on over 4,000 exoplanets and their host stars.

The data set can be found here: https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/TblView/nph-tblView?app=ExoTbls&config=compositepars

Downloading the data set as a .csv file, then importing into this notebook results in a parsing error caused by commented ('#') column descriptions in the first 109 rows. The code and output cell immediately below will demonstrate this if the code is uncommented. The following code and output cells remedy this issue, so that we may begin working with the data set.

Data Cleaning

As shown above, this data set contains over 100 columns, most of which are not relevant to this particular study. For example, for each column consisting of some measured value, there are two additional columns - one with a lower error bound, and another with an upper error bound. There are also columns with hyperlinks used as references. Columns such as these (and others) which are not needed for this project will be dropped using the code below. In addition, the column names/headers are a bit cumbersome, so I have taken the liberty to rename them for ease of understanding among non-astrophysicists (a general audience). Finally, null values are dropped, and we inspect the first and last few rows of our cleaned data set.

4. Methods¶

Exoplanet Habitability vs. Capstone Practicality

Ultimately, a planet suitable for human colonization will need to be habitable. The Planetary Habitability Laboratory at The University of Puerto Rico at Arecibo provides a set of habitability criteria here: http://phl.upr.edu/projects/habitable-exoplanets-catalog/methods. According to their research, there are currently 55 exoplanets which are considered habitable.

As mentioned earlier in this presentation, parameter ranges of key variables will be determined to maintain some semblance of exoplanet habitability while retaining adequate sample sizes. While this approach allows for the pursuit of statistically significant results, it also means that the vast majority of exoplanets analyzed in this study are likely uninhabitable. Nevertheless, we will set some boundaries for the most crucial parameters.

The code below establishes the following parameters:

7 days <= orbital_period <= 730.5 days (2 years)

Next, we will separate this into two groups: exoplanets with stellar mass < 1, and exoplanets with stellar mass >= 1. As shown below, this results in groups with sample sizes of 1,223 and 878, respectively.

5. Results¶

Now that the data set has been split into two sample groups based on solar mass, distributions for exoplanet mass, orbital period, and distance will be evaluated for normality (based on histogram shape, skewness, and kurtosis), then an appropriate test will be chosen for the sample groups at the 95% confidence interval.

Question 1 (Mass):¶

Is there a statistically significant difference between the average mass of exoplanets orbiting a host star smaller than the sun versus exoplanets with a host star that is as big as or larger than the sun?

Yes.¶

In [8]:
plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
plt.title('Comparison of Average Exoplanet Mass')
plt.ylabel('Earth Masses', rotation=90)
em = sns.pointplot(data=[exo_l['earth_mass'], exo_g['earth_mass']], join=False, color="#bb3f3f")
em.set(xticklabels = ['solar mass < 1', 'solar mass >= 1'])
plt.show()
print(get_95_ci(exo_l['earth_mass'], exo_g['earth_mass']))

The difference in means at the 95% confidence interval (two-tail) is between 59.77656022563728 and 91.07816640543042.

With 95% confidence, exoplanets with a host star greater than or equal to the sun have an average mass that is 60 - 91 earth masses greater than exoplanets that orbit a star smaller than the sun.

In [9]:
stats.kruskal(exo_l['earth_mass'], exo_g['earth_mass'])
Out[9]:
KruskalResult(statistic=44.17703671661882, pvalue=2.999797471423731e-11)

The histograms and descriptive statistics show non-normal distributions, so we used the Kruskal-Wallis test to evaluate these variables. The results indicate a large test statistic paired with a miniscule p-value.

For mass, the null hypothesis is therefore rejected. There is a statistically significant difference between the average mass of exoplanets whose host star is less massive than the sun versus those whose host star is more massive than the sun.

Question 2 (Orbital Period):¶

Is there a statistically significant difference between the average orbital period of exoplanets with a host star smaller than the sun versus exoplanets orbiting a star that is as big as or larger than the sun?

Yes.¶

The difference in means at the 95% confidence interval (two-tail) is between 19.934477741466043 and 41.333482411344434.

With 95% confidence, exoplanets with a host star greater than or equal to the sun have an average orbital period that is 20 - 41 days longer than exoplanets that orbit a star smaller than the sun.

In [12]:
stats.kruskal(exo_l['orbital_period'], exo_g['orbital_period'])
Out[12]:
KruskalResult(statistic=11.318340153612553, pvalue=0.0007674528488073753)

The histograms and descriptive statistics show non-normal distributions, so we again use the Kruskal-Wallis test to evaluate orbital periods. While the test statistic and p-value are not as extreme as they are for mass, they are still sufficient enough to reject the null hypothesis. In other words, there appears to be a statistically significant difference in exoplants' orbital periods based on the mass of their host star.

Question 3 (Distance from our solar system):¶

Is there a statistically significant difference between the average distance of exoplanets with a host star smaller than the sun versus exoplanets orbiting a star that is as big as or larger than the sun?

Yes.¶

In [15]:
print(stats.shapiro(exo_l['dist_parsec']))
print(stats.shapiro(exo_g['dist_parsec']))
print()
stats.kruskal(exo_l['dist_parsec'], exo_g['dist_parsec'])

(0.9456992149353027, 8.493692478086225e-21)
(0.9615125060081482, 1.949914737325604e-14)
Out[15]:
KruskalResult(statistic=101.2596614284515, pvalue=8.068222621944778e-24)

For this variable, the histograms show hints of normality, but are otherwise difficult to draw conclusions from. On the other hand, skewness and kurtosis suggest normality. To be certain, we conduct the Shapiro-Wilk test.

The results above show that while W is close to 1 for both distributions, their p-values are well below the .05 threshold for normality. Therefore, the Kruskal-Wallis test will again be used to determine statistical significance.

The massive test statistic and miniscule p-value in the KruskalResult above dictate that we reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, the difference in mean distance from our solar system to exoplanets whose host star is smaller than the sun is statistically significant when compared to exoplanets with a host star more massive than the sun.

6. Discussion and Recommendations¶

It is remarkable that for the three variables tested in this study, the null hypothesis was rejected. Larger sample sizes would be ideal before drawing conclusions with greater certainty; but this result suggests a strong relationship between the mass of a star, and the characteristics of the planets that orbit it. Also, some of the variables tested in this research may warrant transformation prior to analysis. This will be done in subsequent research using methods further ahead in the Thinkful curriculum (https://courses.thinkful.com/dsbc-model-prep-v1/checkpoint/7).

Research of this type is in its infancy, so as exoplanet data accumulates over time, humanity will further its understanding of the complex relationships among astronomical objects within a solar system. Looking further into the future, we seek to actively apply this knowledge in determining which exoplanets may be suitable for human colonization. For now, we can at least see indications that variables associated with exoplanets depend greatly on the mass of their host stars.

Discussion and Recommendations¶

For all 3 variables tested, the null was rejected.

  • This suggests a strong relationship between the mass of a star and the properties of planets that orbit it.
  • To be certain of this, we need to collect more data, which will take time.
  • Also, there may exist a potential bias...

Potential Bias: Exoplanet Discovery Methods¶

About 88% of exoplanets discovered have orbital periods less than 1 year.

Why might this be?

NASA discusses "5 Ways to Find a Planet" here: https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/alien-worlds/ways-to-find-a-planet/

Each of these methods appear to rely on some interaction between the exoplanet and it's host star. We believe that such interactions are easier to detect, and more often detectable for exoplanets that are closer to their host stars. Naturally, exoplanets closer to stars will have shorter orbital periods than more distant planets. We have contacted NASA to verify that this is the case.
